{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17631525","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17631525"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:28:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:28:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17381"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17381","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17381"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10071"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75494"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10071","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10071"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17381"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61004"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"7773"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23572"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23580"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75494","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75494"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA researcher is investigating predictors of 30-day mortality following cardiac surgery. They have collected the following variables:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EOutcome: Patient survival at 30 days (alive/dead)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPredictors: Age, blood pressure, diabetes status (yes/no), and smoking history (pack-years)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe outcome data is not normally distributed. The researcher wants to model the relationship between these variables and develop a predictive model.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statistical tests would be most appropriate for analysing this data?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Multiple linear regression","Logistic regression","Chi-square test","One-way analysis of variance","Pearson correlation coefficient"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELogistic regression\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate test because:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe outcome is binary (survival yes/no)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere are multiple predictor variables (both continuous and categorical)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe goal is to develop a predictive model\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt does not require the outcome to be normally distributed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options are inappropriate because:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMultiple linear regression\u003C/strong\u003E requires a continuous, normally distributed outcome variable\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChi-square test\u003C/strong\u003E only examines associations between categorical variables and cannot handle continuous predictors\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOne-way analysis of variance\u003C/strong\u003E requires a continuous outcome variable and a single categorical predictor\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPearson correlation coefficient\u003C/strong\u003E only measures the linear relationship between two continuous variables\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELogistic regression can accommodate multiple predictor variables of different types while modelling the probability of a binary outcome, making it ideal for this clinical prediction scenario.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Logistic regression is the optimal statistical test for predicting binary outcomes from multiple predictor variables.","Binary outcomes violate the normality assumption required for linear regression.","Logistic regression can handle both continuous and categorical predictor variables when modelling binary outcomes."],"references":["Sullivan LM. Essentials of biostatistics in public health. 3rd ed. Burlington (MA): Jones \u0026 Bartlett Learning; 2018.","Dawson B, Trapp RG. Basic \u0026 clinical biostatistics. 4th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill; 2004."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61004"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17381"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61004","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61004"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-29T21:25:46+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-30T00:54:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10071"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75494"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","syn